What is genuinely outstanding
The count vs for_each explanation in 1.4 is the best I've seen. The apartment number (count) vs apartment name (for_each) analogy, the exact plan output showing destroy+recreate when you remove the middle element, the clear "always prefer for_each" rule — this is the #1 most-asked Terraform interview question and your answer will be memorable.
Native S3 locking is correctly documented. Most Terraform study material still teaches the old DynamoDB pattern. You have use_lockfile = true, the conditional write mechanism, and the bootstrap problem. This is exactly what current JDs ask for.
The three-state triangle (desired/known/actual) in both 1.1 and 2.1 is pedagogically correct. Most candidates confuse "known state" (tfstate) with "actual state" (AWS). Your documents make the distinction clearly.
state mv + moved blocks both covered in 2.3. The interview trap "you renamed a resource — what happens?" has two answers: the imperative terraform state mv and the declarative moved {} block. Mentioning both signals you're current with the language.
Workspaces vs directory-per-env in 4.1 is accurate and honest. The "prod environments need structural differences (monitoring, scaling) that dev doesn't" argument is the correct reason to prefer directories. Most candidates just say "separate state files" without explaining why workspaces fall short.
Lifecycle rules in 5.2 are production-accurate. The create_before_destroy + name_prefix gotcha (both resources temporarily have the same name → conflict), the database pattern with both prevent_destroy AND deletion_protection = true (belt and suspenders), and the ignore_changes anti-pattern warning ("don't use it to hide drift you should fix") — all correct.
Secrets hierarchy in 4.3 is honest. Saying "the password is still in terraform.tfstate — this is Terraform's limitation" rather than pretending random_password solves the problem is the truthful answer. Interviewers respect this.

4 gaps that need fixing
Gap 1 (Priority 1 — significant): Data sources have no dedicated coverage. This is the most notable gap across all 19 files. data "aws_ami", data "aws_availability_zones", data "aws_caller_identity", data "aws_vpc", data "aws_eks_cluster" all appear in your code examples but the fundamental concept is never explained. "Resources create and manage things. Data sources read existing things Terraform doesn't manage." This question appears in virtually every Terraform screening interview.
What to add: A new Phase-1-Core-Language/1.5-data-sources.md covering the resource vs data source distinction, the 6 data sources you'll use in every real project, filter blocks for querying by attributes, and lifecycle behaviour (data sources refresh on every plan).
Gap 2 (Priority 2 — interview exposure): Variable loading precedence is not documented. Your 1.2 covers variable declaration thoroughly but doesn't explain which source wins when multiple sources provide the same variable. The order (lowest to highest): default in code → terraform.tfvars → *.auto.tfvars (alphabetical) → TF_VAR_* environment variables → -var flag → -var-file flag. The *.auto.tfvars being silently loaded is a real source of production bugs — a teammate can add one and every other engineer picks it up without knowing.
What to add: A "Variable Loading Order" section at the end of 1.2, with a precedence table and a worked example.
Gap 3 (Priority 3 — interview trap): Partial apply recovery is not covered. This is explicitly in the roadmap as a senior question. When terraform apply fails after creating 3 of 10 resources, Terraform writes state after each successful resource. The correct answer: run terraform plan to see what's in state and what remains, fix the error, run terraform apply again — it only attempts remaining resources. Also: the -target flag for surgical apply, with the explicit warning it creates state drift risk.
What to add: A "Partial Apply Recovery" section in 2.3-state-commands.md.
Gap 4 (Priority 4 — project readiness): No capstone project reference. You have every individual piece but no assembled picture of a complete Terraform project. You could build one — you have the knowledge — but you'll make architectural decisions without a checklist. When an interviewer says "walk me through how you'd design Terraform for a 3-tier AWS application," the answer needs to cover: directory layout, which modules, dependency order, how variables flow from env tfvars through module composition, and CI/CD integration.
What to add: Phase-4-Production/4.0-capstone-project-structure.md — the complete reference showing how everything wires together for VPC + EKS + RDS + Secrets Manager.

Interview readiness — direct answer
Yes, with one caveat. Fix the data sources gap first. Every other topic is covered at the depth that closes senior interviews. The questions you can answer confidently today: state and why it exists, count vs for_each, multi-environment strategy, workspaces as the wrong answer for prod, renaming a resource without destroying it, secrets handling and the state limitation, CI/CD with OIDC, lifecycle rules in production. The questions that need the fixes: data sources, partial apply recovery, variable precedence under pressure.
Project build readiness — direct answer
Mostly yes. You can write a VPC module, compose it with EKS and RDS modules, set up remote state with native S3 locking, handle secrets with random_password + Secrets Manager, configure multi-environment directories, and set up the CI/CD pipeline with OIDC. The data source gap will briefly block you when configuring the Kubernetes provider from EKS cluster data. The missing capstone document means you'll need to make architectural decisions without a reference — which is fine if you've done the practice exercises.
The gap from 9.2 to 10 is almost entirely about doing the hands-on exercises, not writing more content. Two hours of writing closes the gaps. The remaining points come from applying it.